{
  "Approximately what percentage of energy is transferred from one trophic level to the next in a typical ecosystem?": "",
  "10%": "",
  "50%": "",
  "1%": "",
  "90%": "",
  "Only about 10% of the energy at one trophic level is passed to the next; the rest is lost primarily as heat through cellular respiration.": "",
  "Which organisms form the base of nearly all food chains by converting solar energy into chemical energy?": "",
  "Primary consumers": "",
  "Producers (autotrophs)": "",
  "Decomposers": "",
  "Secondary consumers": "",
  "Producers such as plants and algae use photosynthesis to convert solar energy into chemical energy, forming the foundation of food chains.": "",
  "What happens to most of the energy consumed by organisms at each trophic level?": "",
  "It is stored as biomass": "",
  "It is lost as heat through cellular respiration": "",
  "It is recycled back to producers": "",
  "It is converted to inorganic nutrients": "",
  "At each trophic level, roughly 90% of the energy is lost as heat during cellular respiration, which is why energy flow is one-directional and decreases at higher levels.": "",
  "Which law of thermodynamics explains why energy is lost as heat at each trophic level?": "",
  "Third law of thermodynamics": "",
  "Law of conservation of mass": "",
  "First law of thermodynamics": "",
  "Second law of thermodynamics": "",
  "The second law of thermodynamics states that energy transformations increase entropy; during each transfer, some energy is degraded to heat, making it unavailable for work.": "",
  "In an energy pyramid, which trophic level contains the most energy?": "",
  "Tertiary consumers": "",
  "Producers": "",
  "Producers at the base of the energy pyramid contain the most energy because energy is lost at each successive trophic level.": "",
  "Why are there typically fewer trophic levels in aquatic ecosystems compared to terrestrial ecosystems?": "",
  "Water conducts energy better than air": "",
  "Energy losses at each level limit the number of levels an ecosystem can support": "",
  "Aquatic producers are more efficient": "",
  "Sunlight cannot penetrate deep water": "",
  "Because only about 10% of energy transfers between levels, ecosystems have a limited number of trophic levels they can sustain; this constraint applies universally but is especially visible in aquatic systems with lower overall productivity.": "",
  "What is the relationship between Net Primary Productivity (NPP) and Gross Primary Productivity (GPP)?": "",
  "NPP and GPP are the same thing": "",
  "NPP = GPP + Respiration": "",
  "NPP = GPP - Respiration": "",
  "NPP = GPP x Respiration": "",
  "NPP equals GPP minus the energy used by producers for their own respiration. NPP represents the energy actually available to consumers.": "",
  "Decomposers play a critical role in energy flow because they:": "",
  "Increase the total energy in an ecosystem": "",
  "Create new energy from dead organic matter": "",
  "Transfer energy from dead organisms back into the nutrient pool": "",
  "Convert heat energy back into chemical energy": "",
  "Decomposers break down dead organic matter, releasing nutrients back into the ecosystem and utilizing the remaining chemical energy, though they also lose energy as heat.": "",
  "Which biome typically has the highest net primary productivity?": "",
  "Temperate grassland": "",
  "Tundra": "",
  "Desert": "",
  "Tropical rainforest": "",
  "Tropical rainforests have the highest NPP due to abundant sunlight, warmth, and rainfall year-round, which maximizes photosynthetic output.": "",
  "Energy flow in an ecosystem is described as one-directional because:": "",
  "Energy enters as sunlight and exits as heat, never cycling back": "",
  "Energy flows from consumers back to producers": "",
  "Energy only moves through one food chain": "",
  "Energy can be recycled like nutrients": "",
  "Unlike nutrients, which cycle through ecosystems, energy flows in one direction: it enters as solar radiation, passes through trophic levels, and is ultimately lost as heat.": "",
  "What is a trophic level?": "",
  "The amount of solar radiation an ecosystem receives": "",
  "The geographic range of a species": "",
  "The feeding position of an organism in a food chain or food web": "",
  "A measure of biodiversity in an ecosystem": "",
  "A trophic level is the position an organism occupies in a food chain, such as producer, primary consumer, secondary consumer, or tertiary consumer.": "",
  "What does the term 'primary productivity' mean in ecology?": "",
  "The rate at which consumers convert food into biomass": "",
  "The total number of producers in an ecosystem": "",
  "The speed at which decomposition occurs": "",
  "The rate at which producers capture and store energy through photosynthesis": "",
  "Primary productivity is the rate at which producers (autotrophs) capture solar energy and convert it to chemical energy via photosynthesis, forming the energy base of the ecosystem.": "",
  "What is biomass?": "",
  "The total dry weight of organic matter in organisms at a given trophic level or area": "",
  "The amount of water in living organisms": "",
  "The total energy consumed by all organisms": "",
  "The total number of organisms in an ecosystem": "",
  "Biomass refers to the total dry mass of living organic matter in a particular trophic level, community, or area, and is often used to quantify energy stored in living systems.": "",
  "What does 'gross primary productivity (GPP)' refer to?": "",
  "The energy stored in fossil fuels over geological time": "",
  "The energy available to herbivores after producers respire": "",
  "The total energy captured by producers through photosynthesis before any is used for respiration": "",
  "The net energy gain of an entire ecosystem": "",
  "GPP is the total amount of energy captured by producers through photosynthesis, including the portion they will use for their own metabolic processes.": "",
  "What is meant by 'net primary productivity (NPP)'?": "",
  "The energy available to consumers after producers have used some for respiration": "",
  "The gross energy minus the energy lost through decomposition": "",
  "The productivity of secondary consumers only": "",
  "The total energy captured by all organisms in an ecosystem": "",
  "NPP is the energy that remains after producers use some of their GPP for cellular respiration. It represents the energy actually available to be consumed by herbivores and other organisms.": "",
  "What does the term 'food web' mean?": "",
  "A single linear pathway showing who eats whom": "",
  "The total amount of food available in a habitat": "",
  "A diagram showing nutrient cycling only": "",
  "A complex network of interconnected food chains in an ecosystem": "",
  "A food web is a complex, interconnected network of multiple food chains that shows the many feeding relationships among organisms in an ecosystem.": "",
  "What is an energy pyramid?": "",
  "A model showing how energy is created by producers": "",
  "A diagram showing the cycling of nutrients through an ecosystem": "",
  "A chart comparing energy use across different biomes": "",
  "A graphical representation of the amount of energy at each trophic level, with the most energy at the base": "",
  "An energy pyramid is a diagram that shows the relative amount of energy available at each trophic level, always widest at the producer level and narrowing toward top predators.": "",
  "What does the term 'autotroph' mean?": "",
  "An organism that produces its own food from inorganic substances using light or chemical energy": "",
  "An organism that lives in symbiosis with another species": "",
  "An organism that breaks down dead organic matter": "",
  "An organism that feeds on other organisms for energy": "",
  "An autotroph is a self-feeding organism that produces its own organic molecules from inorganic raw materials, using energy from sunlight (photoautotroph) or chemical reactions (chemoautotroph).": "",
  "What is meant by 'ecological efficiency'?": "",
  "The percentage of energy transferred from one trophic level to the next": "",
  "The total number of species in an ecosystem": "",
  "The speed at which an ecosystem recovers from disturbance": "",
  "The rate of nutrient recycling in a community": "",
  "Ecological efficiency is the proportion of energy at one trophic level that is incorporated into biomass at the next trophic level, typically averaging around 10%.": "",
  "What does 'heterotroph' mean?": "",
  "An organism that only lives in aquatic environments": "",
  "An organism that can produce its own food": "",
  "An organism that obtains energy by consuming other organisms": "",
  "An organism that decomposes inorganic matter": "",
  "A heterotroph is an organism that cannot make its own food and must obtain energy by consuming other organisms or organic matter, including herbivores, carnivores, and decomposers.": "",
  "A marine biologist measures that phytoplankton in a coastal bay fix 10,000 kcal/m²/year through photosynthesis and use 6,000 kcal/m²/year for their own respiration. What is the net primary productivity available to zooplankton and other consumers?": "",
  "6,000 kcal/m²/year": "",
  "16,000 kcal/m²/year": "",
  "4,000 kcal/m²/year": "",
  "10,000 kcal/m²/year": "",
  "NPP = GPP - Respiration = 10,000 - 6,000 = 4,000 kcal/m²/year. This is the energy actually available for zooplankton and higher trophic levels to consume.": "",
  "A farmer is deciding whether to grow corn to feed cattle or to grow corn for direct human consumption. Based on the 10% rule of energy transfer, which approach would feed more people and why?": "",
  "Both approaches feed the same number of people": "",
  "Feeding cattle, because beef has more calories per gram": "",
  "Growing corn for direct human consumption, because eating at a lower trophic level captures more of the original energy": "",
  "Feeding cattle, because animals concentrate nutrients more efficiently": "",
  "Eating lower on the food chain is more energy-efficient. When humans eat corn directly, they access the full energy of that trophic level; routing it through cattle loses about 90% of the energy at each transfer.": "",
  "An ecologist studying a lake ecosystem finds that the producer level contains 20,000 kcal of energy. Using the 10% rule, how much energy would be available to secondary consumers (third trophic level)?": "",
  "2,000 kcal": "",
  "20 kcal": "",
  "200 kcal": "",
  "1,000 kcal": "",
  "Producers have 20,000 kcal. Primary consumers get 10% = 2,000 kcal. Secondary consumers get 10% of that = 200 kcal. Energy decreases by a factor of 10 at each trophic level.": "",
  "A coastal city is experiencing algal blooms due to agricultural runoff. Fishermen notice that while algae biomass has increased dramatically, the populations of large predatory fish have not increased proportionally. Which concept best explains this observation?": "",
  "Habitat fragmentation": "",
  "The 10% rule of energy transfer between trophic levels": "",
  "Competitive exclusion principle": "",
  "Genetic drift in fish populations": "",
  "Due to the 10% rule, a large increase in producer biomass translates to progressively smaller increases at higher trophic levels. Predatory fish are several levels removed from algae, so they receive only a tiny fraction of the additional energy.": "",
  "Researchers comparing two ecosystems find that a tropical rainforest has a GPP of 8,000 g C/m²/year and a tundra has a GPP of 200 g C/m²/year. If both lose about 50% to respiration, which ecosystem supports more consumer biomass and why?": "",
  "The tropical rainforest, because its much higher NPP provides far more energy for consumers": "",
  "The tundra, because fewer species means less competition": "",
  "They support equal consumer biomass since both lose 50%": "",
  "The tundra, because cold temperatures preserve energy better": "",
  "The rainforest NPP is 4,000 g C/m²/year versus only 100 g C/m²/year for tundra. Since consumer biomass depends on NPP, the rainforest can support vastly more consumer biomass.": "",
  "A wildlife manager notices that after the removal of wolves from a national park, deer populations exploded and vegetation declined sharply. How does this scenario relate to energy flow concepts?": "",
  "The removal of wolves increased GPP in the ecosystem": "",
  "Wolves were the main producers in the ecosystem": "",
  "Without top predators, primary consumers overgraze producers, disrupting the energy base of the ecosystem": "",
  "Deer populations create more energy for the ecosystem": "",
  "When top predators are removed, unchecked herbivore populations consume excessive producer biomass, reducing NPP and destabilizing energy flow through the entire food web.": "",
  "A fisheries scientist recommends harvesting anchovies (primary consumers) rather than tuna (tertiary consumers) to maximize the food yield from the ocean. Which principle supports this recommendation?": "",
  "The principle of competitive exclusion": "",
  "The ecological efficiency of energy transfer between trophic levels": "",
  "The law of conservation of mass": "",
  "The theory of island biogeography": "",
  "Harvesting at lower trophic levels captures more of the available energy. By the time energy reaches tuna (tertiary consumers), about 99.9% of the original producer energy has been lost as heat.": "",
  "After a volcanic eruption covers a forest in ash, scientists observe that the area's productivity drops to nearly zero. Over the following decades, lichens colonize bare rock, followed by mosses and eventually trees. How does energy flow change during this process?": "",
  "Energy flow remains constant throughout succession": "",
  "Energy flow decreases as more species compete for resources": "",
  "Energy flow only increases once tertiary consumers arrive": "",
  "GPP and NPP gradually increase as more producers establish and grow, supporting increasingly complex food webs": "",
  "During ecological succession, as producer biomass increases, GPP and NPP rise. This growing energy base supports progressively more trophic levels and a more complex food web over time.": "",
  "A city plans to convert vacant lots into urban gardens. An environmental consultant explains that growing vegetables directly for residents is more energy-efficient than using the same land to grow feed for livestock. What ecological principle underlies this advice?": "",
  "Biomagnification of toxins": "",
  "The greenhouse effect": "",
  "Nitrogen fixation by soil bacteria": "",
  "The second law of thermodynamics and the 10% rule of trophic energy transfer": "",
  "Eating plants directly (one trophic transfer) retains far more energy than routing through livestock (two transfers). The 10% rule means only about 10% of plant energy becomes animal biomass, so direct consumption is more efficient.": "",
